### Brooklyn Park, Minnesota

Brooklyn Park is a [city](/City) situated in the northern reaches of [Hennepin County](/Hennepin_County,_Minnesota), specifically on the western bank of the mighty [Mississippi River](/Mississippi_River). It lies upstream, or north, of the bustling [Twin Cities](/Minneapolis-Saint_Paul) metropolitan area, establishing itself as a significant suburban entity. In fact, it’s the [sixth-largest city](/List_of_cities_in_Minnesota) in the entire state of [Minnesota](/Minnesota). As of the [2020 census](/2020_United_States_census), the population stood at a considerable 86,478 individuals. &#91;4&#93; What's mildly interesting, if you can call it that, is that Brooklyn Park still retains pockets of undeveloped land and active farms. One such place is the historic Eidem Homestead, a working farm from the early 1900s that seems to attract families and school groups on field trips. &#91;6&#93; The city is often described as both a second- and third-tier suburb of Minneapolis. This distinction arises because a substantial portion of the land north of 85th Avenue experienced significant development only after the year 2000. &#91; [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) &#93;

It’s worth noting that [Jesse Ventura](/Jesse_Ventura), a figure known for his career in [WWE](/WWE_Hall_of_Fame) and later as [governor of Minnesota](/1998_Minnesota_gubernatorial_election), served as the mayor of Brooklyn Park from 1991 to 1995. He went on to become governor in 1999, serving until 2003. &#91;7&#93;

Brooklyn Park seems to have a thing for trees and trails. It's officially recognized as a "Tree City USA" and boasts an impressive 47 miles (76 km) of interconnected trails. Complementing this are 67 parks, including the Rush Creek Regional Trail and the northern section of Palmer Lake Park. The Mississippi Gateway Regional Park, situated on the west side of Coon Rapids Dam Regional Park, is another notable green space. For those seeking higher education, the city is home to [Rasmussen University](/Rasmussen_University), [North Hennepin Community College](/North_Hennepin_Community_College), and a campus of [Hennepin Technical College](/Hennepin_Technical_College).

#### History

The formal organization of town government in Brooklyn Park dates back to 1858, initiated by settlers who hailed from Michigan. They christened the area after their home state's [Brooklyn, Michigan](/Brooklyn,_Michigan), which itself was named in honor of [Brooklyn, New York](/Brooklyn,_New_York). Previously known as Brooklyn Township, a portion of it separated in 1911 when the southeastern section incorporated as [Brooklyn Center](/Brooklyn_Center,_Minnesota). The remaining Brooklyn Township was eventually incorporated as the Village of Brooklyn Park in 1954, and then officially became a city in 1969. &#91;7&#93; In a grim turn of events, in 2025, the city became one of the dual epicenters of the [2025 Minnesota lawmaker shootings](/2025_Minnesota_lawmaker_shootings), a tragedy that resulted in the assassination of DFL State Representative [Melissa Hortman](/Melissa_Hortman) and her husband.

#### Geography

According to data from the [United States Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), Brooklyn Park encompasses a total area of 26.549 square miles (68.76 km²). Of this, 26.076 square miles (67.54 km²) is land, while 0.473 square miles (1.23 km²), representing 1.89%, is covered by water. &#91;2&#93; The eastern boundary of the city is defined by the [Mississippi River](/Mississippi_River), which serves as a natural divider from [Coon Rapids](/Coon_Rapids,_Minnesota) and [Fridley](/Fridley,_Minnesota) in [Anoka County](/Anoka_County,_Minnesota).

Major transportation arteries traverse the city. [Interstate 94](/Interstate_94_in_Minnesota) (I-94) and [I-694](/Interstate_694) are situated in the southernmost part of Brooklyn Park. To the west, you'll find [US Highway 169](/U.S._Route_169_in_Minnesota). [Minnesota State Highway 252](/Minnesota_State_Highway_252) (MN 252), a relatively short 4.5-mile (7.2 km) north-south route, runs along the eastern side. Cutting across the northern section of Brooklyn Park is [MN 610](/Minnesota_State_Highway_610), an east-west highway. [County Road 81](/County_Road_81_(Hennepin_County,_Minnesota)) also functions as a primary thoroughfare within the city.

#### Climate

Brooklyn Park experiences a [humid continental climate](/Humid_continental_climate), classified under the [Köppen climate classification](/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification) as Dfa. This means it has hot, humid summers and cold, dry winters.

